NerdHerd

Target IP: 10.10.101.79

Scanning


There are five TCP ports open on the target machine. The FTP application allows anonymous login, so I will start my enumeration from there.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

I found two files using FTP: youfoundme.png and hellon3rd.txt.


The first file is interesting, as I was able to extract four files using the command binwalk -e youfoundme.png. I also obtained a possible username fijbxslz by using the command exiftool -a -u youfoundme.png on the image. Doing a Google search for this string leads to Vigenere Cipher results.


The text file hellon3rd.txt contains the message above. leet refers to 1337 port on the target machine.

Port 1337: HTTP

The default Apache webpage is displayed for this application. However, two message boxes are shown which are not helpful. The HTML source-code contains the interesting code above, but it was not helpful at all.


Doing a directory search against this application shows /admin. Browsing to this webpage shows the content above.


And the source code of /admin/index.php contains the message above. There are two base64 strings. Decoding aGVoZWdvdTwdasddHlvdQ== output hehegou<jÇ][ÝD; the first part of this string is interesting. And decoding Y2liYXJ0b3dza2k= gave me cibartowski.


Using enum4linux against the target machine output the interesting entry above. There is a user called chuck. However, a password is required for this user. I tried spraying different possible passwords I obtained from previous enumeration, but they did not work.


I got stuck here and needed a hint. Apparently it is possible to decode the vigenere string fijbxslz by using the key birdist. The video contained a hint. After decoding it, the password easypass is given. Using the password easypass, now I have access to the SMB share as chuck. There is a file called secr3t.txt which states there is a hidden directory called /this1sn0tadirect0ry.


Browsing to /this1sn0tadirect0ry shows the content above. Now I have the credential chuck:th1s41ntmypa5s.

Exploitation


Using the SSH login, now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation



Running uname -a shows the host is running 4.4.0-31-generic #50-Ubuntu which is vulnerable to local privilege escalation exploit. I transferred the exploit to the target machine, and ran it. And now I have a root shell on the target machine.
